The warrants were mostly for small amounts, and usually for less than $100. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Penn., Sept. 4.--RICHARD CARTER, foreman of the stone masons employed at Fairmount Park, was shot at and killed by JOSEPH SNYDER, a discharged workman. abstract: M. MAILLEFERT continues his submarine blasts on Ways Reff. Yesterday he exploded about twenty charges of 129 pounds of power each. He has been dredging the debris, and has already carried to shore some 300 tons of rock. The result of his explosions is not known, but he believes that about onequarter of the required amount of rock has been removed.

abstract: CHARLESTON, S.C., Sept. 18.--A terrible accident occurred to the night train from Charleston on the South Carolina Railroad before day light this morning. A large tree had fallen across the trestle at Congaree Swamp, and the engine and part of the train were precipitated into the swamp. The engine blew up, setting the cars and trestle on fire. About 600 feet of trestle was burned. None of the passengers were injured.
